result.execSummary:
The defendant Vanessa M Stewart was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
10:34 am Def in court w/Atty Joseph Geraldson.  Jessica Skemp appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Mark Frise
Belzer:  DOC is turning the restitution over to a divil judgment and will not be extending her probation again.  She's made a good faith effort and making small payments....  She's wanting to move in with her folks in Virginia....  She has a job with them.... There are no probationary needs to identify.  She's done everything else....  I didn't give much notice of this hearing so I know Ms. Skemp has concerns about contacting the victim.
Court:  Mr. Frise, is that correct that she's made a good faith effort as Mr. Belzer describes?
Frise:   Yes....  
Court:  How much restitution is due at this point?
Frise:  $1,823.22 in 14CF-202.   15CM-110 there's no restitution at all.  She's paid $282.
Court:  So there's no question about the 15CM-110 discharging.
Frise:  That would just be the court costs.
Skemp didn't have notice of what this hearing is about and even the correct case is not even on the calendar.
Court:  What we're concerned about is 14CF-202.
Skemp:  The victimin that case is K-Mart.  I don't have concerns about converting that to a judgment vs a citizen victim.  I'm not asking for more time under those circumstances.
COURT:  15CM-110 no restitution and court costs are paid.  Probation is terminated.  In 14CF-202 the victim is K-Mart.  Ms. Stewart has made a good faith effort to pay restitution.  I'll permit that probation to terminate as well.  Any restitution or court costs are converted to a civil judgment.
